1
00:01:20,296 --> 00:01:22,287
[Church bells chiming]

2
00:01:31,073 --> 00:01:32,938
BOTH: Bonjour, monsieur.

3
00:01:34,910 --> 00:01:36,400
Bonjour.

4
00:01:36,445 --> 00:01:38,572
Bonjour, monsieur.
Say bonjour.

5
00:01:38,614 --> 00:01:41,014
Bonjour.

6
00:01:41,050 --> 00:01:42,642
Ahem.

7
00:01:43,753 --> 00:01:45,721
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>Once upon a time...</i>

8
00:01:45,755 --> 00:01:46,915
<i>there was</i>
<i>a quiet little village...</i>

9
00:01:46,956 --> 00:01:48,856
<i>in the French countryside...</i>

10
00:01:48,891 --> 00:01:51,985
<i>whose people believed</i>
<i>in tranquilite.</i>

11
00:01:52,028 --> 00:01:53,723
[Doors bang shut]

12
00:01:53,763 --> 00:01:56,129
<i>Tranquility.</i>

13
00:01:56,165 --> 00:01:57,530
[Organ playing]

14
00:01:57,566 --> 00:01:59,431
<i>CONGREGATION SINGING:</i>
<i>Come Holy Ghost</i>

15
00:01:59,468 --> 00:02:02,096
<i>Creator come</i>

16
00:02:02,138 --> 00:02:07,269
<i>From Thy bright</i>
<i>heavenly throne</i>

17
00:02:07,310 --> 00:02:13,180
<i>Come take possession</i>
<i>of our souls</i>

18
00:02:13,215 --> 00:02:20,587
<i>And make them all Thine own</i>

19
00:02:20,623 --> 00:02:23,353
<i>Far from us drive our...</i>

20
00:02:23,392 --> 00:02:25,724
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>If you lived in this village...</i>

21
00:02:25,761 --> 00:02:28,252
<i>you understood</i>
<i>what was expected of you.</i>

22
00:02:28,297 --> 00:02:31,994
<i>CONGREGATION SINGING:</i>
<i>...unto us bring</i>

23
00:02:32,034 --> 00:02:33,934
<i>And through all...</i>

24
00:02:33,969 --> 00:02:38,235
<i>STORYTELLER: You knew your</i>
<i>place in the scheme of things.</i>

25
00:02:38,274 --> 00:02:42,904
<i>And if you happened to forget,</i>
<i>someone would help remind you.</i>

26
00:02:42,945 --> 00:02:43,934
[Snorts]

27
00:02:55,458 --> 00:02:57,653
The season of Lent is upon us.

28
00:02:57,693 --> 00:03:01,993
This is, of course,
a time of abstinence.

29
00:03:02,031 --> 00:03:06,297
Hopefully,
also a time of reflection.

30
00:03:06,335 --> 00:03:09,361
Above all,
let this be for us a time...

31
00:03:10,673 --> 00:03:13,574
<i>PERE:</i>
<i>a time of sincere penitence.</i>

32
00:03:13,609 --> 00:03:15,076
[Dog whimpers]

33
00:03:15,111 --> 00:03:18,080
<i>PERE: It is a time</i>
<i>to stand up and be counted.</i>

34
00:03:18,114 --> 00:03:19,479
<i>STORYTELLER: In this village...</i>

35
00:03:19,515 --> 00:03:23,076
<i>if you saw something</i>
<i>you weren't supposed to see...</i>

36
00:03:23,119 --> 00:03:25,019
<i>you learned</i>
<i>to look the other way.</i>

37
00:03:25,054 --> 00:03:26,783
<i>PERE:</i>
<i>This is a time for Christ.</i>

38
00:03:26,822 --> 00:03:29,689
<i>When you reflect,</i>
<i>he knows what you reflect on.</i>

39
00:03:29,725 --> 00:03:30,919
<i>STORYTELLER: If by chance...</i>

40
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:34,054
<i>your hopes</i>
<i>had been disappointed...</i>

41
00:03:34,096 --> 00:03:37,827
<i>you learned</i>
<i>never to ask for more.</i>

42
00:03:37,867 --> 00:03:40,893
<i>PERE: He knows for what</i>
<i>you must be forgiven.</i>

43
00:03:40,936 --> 00:03:42,233
[Wind whistling]

44
00:03:42,271 --> 00:03:45,502
<i>So in this Year of Our Lord,</i>
<i>1959, things...</i>

45
00:03:45,541 --> 00:03:49,136
<i>STORYTELLER: So,</i>
<i>through good times and bad...</i>

46
00:03:49,178 --> 00:03:50,975
<i>famine and feast...</i>

47
00:03:51,013 --> 00:03:54,847
<i>the villagers held fast</i>
<i>to their traditions.</i>

48
00:03:54,884 --> 00:03:56,784
<i>Until...</i>

49
00:03:56,819 --> 00:03:57,790
<i>one winter day...</i>

50
00:03:57,825 --> 00:03:58,762
<i>one winter day...</i>

51
00:03:58,803 --> 00:04:02,637
<i>a sly wind</i>
<i>blew in from the north.</i>

52
00:04:08,646 --> 00:04:10,944
<i>PERE: Where will we find truth?</i>

53
00:04:10,982 --> 00:04:12,779
[Wind blowing]

54
00:04:12,817 --> 00:04:14,580
Where do we start looking?

55
00:04:14,619 --> 00:04:16,587
[Wind whistling]

56
00:04:16,621 --> 00:04:18,282
<i>PERE: Where will we find truth?</i>

57
00:04:18,323 --> 00:04:19,756
<i>We will find it...</i>

58
00:05:11,109 --> 00:05:13,703
[Door closes]

59
00:05:19,450 --> 00:05:20,712
Who the hell are you?

60
00:05:20,752 --> 00:05:23,812
Oh, uh...

61
00:05:23,855 --> 00:05:27,291
We're here about the patisserie.

62
00:05:27,325 --> 00:05:29,759
We'd like to rent it...

63
00:05:29,794 --> 00:05:31,557
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>and the apartment above.</i>

64
00:05:31,596 --> 00:05:32,995
Where are you from?

65
00:05:33,031 --> 00:05:37,331
Well, we lived in Andalucia
for a while.

66
00:05:37,368 --> 00:05:41,168
Let me see.
Before that, Vienna...

67
00:05:41,206 --> 00:05:44,369
and before that...

68
00:05:44,409 --> 00:05:46,536
- Athens.
- Pavia.

69
00:05:46,578 --> 00:05:48,705
<i>ANOUK:</i>
<i>Pantoufle hated it there.</i>

70
00:05:48,746 --> 00:05:51,112
Pantoufle is her kangaroo.

71
00:05:51,149 --> 00:05:53,014
But he can't hop.

72
00:05:53,051 --> 00:05:56,316
Bad leg. War injury, huh?

73
00:06:12,937 --> 00:06:15,929
I'll expect you to keep it
in good condition.

74
00:06:20,945 --> 00:06:22,708
[Door slams]

75
00:06:22,747 --> 00:06:24,214
[Vianne chuckles]

76
00:06:24,249 --> 00:06:26,240
[Humming]

77
00:06:33,558 --> 00:06:35,753
<i>ANOUK:</i>
<i>What a nice town this is.</i>

78
00:06:35,793 --> 00:06:37,420
Don't you think so, Mama?

79
00:06:37,462 --> 00:06:39,521
It's a lovely town.

80
00:06:41,299 --> 00:06:44,962
Mama, Pantoufle wants to know
how long we can stay.

81
00:06:45,003 --> 00:06:48,871
<i>VIANNE: Oh, tell Pantoufle</i>
<i>not to worry.</i>

82
00:06:48,906 --> 00:06:50,373
[Whispering]

83
00:06:50,408 --> 00:06:52,808
Time for bed.
What story tonight?

84
00:06:52,844 --> 00:06:57,247
Pantoufle wants to hear
about grandmere and grandpere.

85
00:06:57,282 --> 00:06:59,580
Not tonight, Anouska.

86
00:06:59,617 --> 00:07:01,983
<i>ANOUK: You always say that.</i>

87
00:07:02,020 --> 00:07:04,580
Tell about
grandmere and grandpere.

88
00:07:04,622 --> 00:07:07,147
Not tonight.

89
00:07:07,191 --> 00:07:10,285
How about the princess
and the pirates?

90
00:07:10,328 --> 00:07:11,920
<i>ANOUK: OK.</i>

91
00:07:13,331 --> 00:07:14,923
<i>ANOUK: Prepare to fire!</i>

92
00:07:14,966 --> 00:07:17,628
All hands on deck!

93
00:07:17,669 --> 00:07:20,570
<i>ANOUK: Ready, aim...</i>

94
00:07:20,605 --> 00:07:21,902
fire!

95
00:07:24,208 --> 00:07:26,802
<i>REYNAUD: Forgive the intrusion.</i>

96
00:07:26,844 --> 00:07:28,675
<i>VIANNE: It's a pleasure.</i>

97
00:07:31,316 --> 00:07:33,284
ANOUK: Sorry, monsieur.

98
00:07:33,318 --> 00:07:36,651
- Pirate attack.
- Of course.

99
00:07:36,688 --> 00:07:38,155
What is your name?

100
00:07:38,189 --> 00:07:40,350
Anouk. What's yours?

101
00:07:40,391 --> 00:07:43,326
I am the Comte de Reynaud
at your service.

102
00:07:43,361 --> 00:07:44,988
<i>ANOUK: A real one?</i>

103
00:07:45,029 --> 00:07:47,190
Like the Comte de Monte Cristo?

104
00:07:47,231 --> 00:07:49,791
Ah-ah!
He was not a real one.

105
00:07:49,834 --> 00:07:52,302
<i>VIANNE: To what do we owe</i>
<i>the honor of your visit?</i>

106
00:07:52,337 --> 00:07:54,635
Well, as mayor of Lansquenet...

107
00:07:54,672 --> 00:07:57,072
I want to welcome you
to the community...

108
00:07:57,108 --> 00:08:00,709
and to invite you to worship
with us at mass on Sunday.

109
00:08:00,744 --> 00:08:04,311
That's very kind of you,
but actually we don't attend.

110
00:08:07,285 --> 00:08:09,981
<i>VIANNE: We're glad to be</i>
<i>so near the church, though.</i>

111
00:08:10,021 --> 00:08:12,285
We'll enjoy
singing with the bells.

112
00:08:12,323 --> 00:08:15,952
The bells are not intended
as an entertainment, Madame.

113
00:08:15,993 --> 00:08:17,893
They are a solemn call
to worship for...

114
00:08:17,929 --> 00:08:19,794
<i>VIANNE: Mademoiselle.</i>

115
00:08:19,831 --> 00:08:20,957
I beg your pardon?

116
00:08:20,998 --> 00:08:22,989
Mademoiselle.
I've never been married...

117
00:08:23,034 --> 00:08:25,798
but feel free to call me Vianne.

118
00:08:28,172 --> 00:08:31,403
I hope you'll stop by when
I open for business next week.

119
00:08:31,442 --> 00:08:34,138
Yes.

120
00:08:34,178 --> 00:08:37,909
Yes, opening a patisserie
during the holy Lenten fast.

121
00:08:37,949 --> 00:08:39,644
I could imagine better timing.

122
00:08:39,684 --> 00:08:42,152
Oh, but it's not going
to be a patisserie.

123
00:08:42,186 --> 00:08:43,813
Then what do you intend to...

124
00:08:43,855 --> 00:08:45,755
It's a surprise.

125
00:08:45,790 --> 00:08:48,384
It was sweet of you to drop by.

126
00:08:56,401 --> 00:08:57,834
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>The Comte de Reynaud...</i>

127
00:08:57,869 --> 00:09:02,670
<i>was a student of history,</i>
<i>and therefore a patient man.</i>

128
00:09:02,707 --> 00:09:06,905
<i>He trusted the wisdom</i>
<i>of generations past.</i>

129
00:09:06,944 --> 00:09:11,711
<i>Like his ancestors, he watched</i>
<i>over the little village...</i>

130
00:09:11,749 --> 00:09:14,240
<i>and led by his own example...</i>

131
00:09:14,285 --> 00:09:18,244
<i>hard work, modesty...</i>

132
00:09:18,289 --> 00:09:20,257
<i>self-discipline.</i>

133
00:09:32,670 --> 00:09:35,104
I have completed
the 18th Century.

134
00:09:35,139 --> 00:09:37,539
[Sniffling]

135
00:09:37,575 --> 00:09:39,202
Madame Clairmont.

136
00:09:41,078 --> 00:09:43,979
Your letter to the editor,
Monsieur le Comte.

137
00:09:44,015 --> 00:09:47,473
This paragraph about family
and tradition, it's...

138
00:09:47,518 --> 00:09:49,611
it's beautiful.

139
00:09:49,654 --> 00:09:51,451
Oh! Ha ha.

140
00:09:51,489 --> 00:09:53,821
Well, thank you.

141
00:09:53,858 --> 00:09:55,655
I value your opinion.

142
00:09:55,693 --> 00:09:57,558
[Dog barking]

143
00:09:57,595 --> 00:09:59,722
[Door closes]

144
00:10:01,866 --> 00:10:04,027
<i>VIANNE: Bonjour! Hello!</i>

145
00:10:04,068 --> 00:10:05,296
<i>REYNAUD: May I ask...</i>

146
00:10:05,336 --> 00:10:08,965
<i>have you been in contact</i>
<i>with your mother recently?</i>

147
00:10:09,006 --> 00:10:10,837
<i>CAROLINE: Why?</i>

148
00:10:10,875 --> 00:10:12,934
She seems to have
rented out the patisserie.

149
00:10:12,977 --> 00:10:15,411
<i>CAROLINE: Oh.</i>

150
00:10:15,446 --> 00:10:19,576
I haven't talked to my mother
in quite a while.

151
00:10:19,617 --> 00:10:21,642
I'm sorry.
I did not mean to pry.

152
00:10:21,686 --> 00:10:24,416
Oh, don't be silly.

153
00:10:24,455 --> 00:10:26,616
I have no secrets from you.

154
00:10:28,125 --> 00:10:30,787
How is the comtesse
enjoying Venice?

155
00:10:30,828 --> 00:10:34,855
The comtesse?
Oh, she's fine, thank you.

156
00:10:34,899 --> 00:10:37,561
Yes,
she's enjoying it very much.

157
00:10:38,903 --> 00:10:41,235
Venice.

158
00:10:44,208 --> 00:10:45,675
[Sighs]

159
00:10:51,616 --> 00:10:54,176
<i>WOMAN: I heard she was</i>
<i>some kind of radical.</i>

160
00:11:18,942 --> 00:11:20,910
I heard she's an atheist.

161
00:11:20,944 --> 00:11:22,639
What's that?

162
00:11:22,679 --> 00:11:24,977
Don't know.

163
00:11:34,258 --> 00:11:35,623
<i>GUILLAUME: Come on, Charly.</i>

164
00:11:35,659 --> 00:11:36,648
[Whimpering]

165
00:11:37,995 --> 00:11:39,986
Come on.

166
00:12:04,088 --> 00:12:05,578
Oh!

167
00:12:31,782 --> 00:12:33,943
Uhh! Oh!

168
00:12:33,984 --> 00:12:35,451
You should be more careful!

169
00:12:35,486 --> 00:12:38,387
- So sorry, Madame.
- I'm sorry.

170
00:12:38,422 --> 00:12:39,650
VIANNE: Are you all right?

171
00:12:39,690 --> 00:12:41,282
CAROLINE: I'm fine, I'm fine.

172
00:12:41,325 --> 00:12:44,158
VIANNE: I'm sorry. Do you want
to come in and sit down?

173
00:12:44,194 --> 00:12:46,219
CAROLINE: Please don't
trouble yourself. I'm fine.

174
00:12:46,263 --> 00:12:48,891
VIANNE: No, it's no trouble.
I'm Vianne Rocher.

175
00:12:48,932 --> 00:12:50,456
Caroline Clairmont.

176
00:12:50,501 --> 00:12:51,866
I'm the daughter
of your landlady.

177
00:12:51,902 --> 00:12:52,869
This is my son Luc.

178
00:12:52,903 --> 00:12:55,269
VIANNE: Hello.
And this is my Anouk.

179
00:12:55,305 --> 00:12:57,500
Come in, please,
where it's warm.

180
00:12:57,541 --> 00:12:59,099
Try this.

181
00:12:59,143 --> 00:13:01,407
I bet you've never
had hot chocolate...

182
00:13:01,445 --> 00:13:03,936
made from
a 2,000-year-old recipe.

183
00:13:03,981 --> 00:13:05,471
Thank you, but no. Luc.

184
00:13:06,650 --> 00:13:07,981
<i>CAROLINE: No.</i>

185
00:13:10,687 --> 00:13:11,654
<i>WOMAN: What's this?</i>

186
00:13:11,688 --> 00:13:14,350
What do you see, Madame,
in this?

187
00:13:14,391 --> 00:13:15,756
Sorry?

188
00:13:15,792 --> 00:13:17,384
VIANNE:
What does it look like to you?

189
00:13:17,427 --> 00:13:19,987
Just say the first thing
that comes into your mind.

190
00:13:23,167 --> 00:13:24,464
<i>WOMAN: Um...</i>

191
00:13:24,501 --> 00:13:27,334
A woman riding a wild horse?

192
00:13:27,371 --> 00:13:28,531
Ha!

193
00:13:28,572 --> 00:13:30,540
- Ooh!
- Oh, silly answer.

194
00:13:30,574 --> 00:13:32,098
Oh, no.
There are no silly answers.

195
00:13:32,142 --> 00:13:34,042
The pepper triangle,
that's for you.

196
00:13:34,077 --> 00:13:36,102
A tiny hint of chili pepper...

197
00:13:36,146 --> 00:13:38,842
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>to play against the sweetness.</i>

198
00:13:39,850 --> 00:13:42,375
Tangy, adventurous.

199
00:13:51,428 --> 00:13:53,396
What do you see?

200
00:13:55,832 --> 00:13:57,561
I see teeth.

201
00:13:58,569 --> 00:14:00,366
<i>LUC: I see blood...</i>

202
00:14:00,404 --> 00:14:02,964
<i>and a skull.</i>

203
00:14:05,409 --> 00:14:07,172
<i>Very dark.</i>

204
00:14:07,211 --> 00:14:09,679
<i>VIANNE: Bitter chocolate.</i>
<i>That's your favorite.</i>

205
00:14:09,713 --> 00:14:12,773
<i>CAROLINE: Which will</i>
<i>have to wait five weeks more.</i>

206
00:14:12,816 --> 00:14:14,647
Lent. Thank you.

207
00:14:16,253 --> 00:14:19,654
We must run along.
It's been nice to meet you.

208
00:14:20,691 --> 00:14:21,953
My pleasure.

209
00:14:21,992 --> 00:14:24,324
<i>ANOUK: Pantoufle, come on!</i>
<i>Pirate attack!</i>

210
00:14:25,596 --> 00:14:28,724
<i>WOMAN: How much are</i>
<i>those chili things, please?</i>

211
00:14:28,765 --> 00:14:30,357
<i>VIANNE: 4.50 a box.</i>

212
00:14:30,400 --> 00:14:31,833
Could you put a ribbon on it?

213
00:14:31,868 --> 00:14:33,199
Mm-hmm.

214
00:14:33,237 --> 00:14:34,795
<i>WOMAN: Then I can pretend</i>
<i>they are from my husband.</i>

215
00:14:34,838 --> 00:14:36,430
Of course.

216
00:14:36,473 --> 00:14:38,839
[Woman laughing]

217
00:14:38,875 --> 00:14:41,400
[Whispering]

218
00:14:41,445 --> 00:14:43,504
<i>WOMAN: Josephine Muscat.</i>

219
00:14:43,547 --> 00:14:45,708
<i>She waltzes to her own tune.</i>

220
00:14:47,517 --> 00:14:50,384
And these are for your husband...

221
00:14:50,420 --> 00:14:53,583
unrefined coco nips
from Guatemala...

222
00:14:53,624 --> 00:14:55,421
to awaken the passions.

223
00:14:55,459 --> 00:14:57,518
Ha!

224
00:14:57,561 --> 00:15:00,257
You've obviously
never met my husband.

225
00:15:00,297 --> 00:15:03,789
You've obviously
never tried these.

226
00:15:09,172 --> 00:15:10,935
[Snoring]

227
00:15:10,974 --> 00:15:12,965
[Music plays on radio]

228
00:15:24,988 --> 00:15:27,752
Don't be pathetic.

229
00:15:30,360 --> 00:15:32,351
[Kids shouting]

230
00:15:38,001 --> 00:15:39,992
[Kids shouting and laughing]

231
00:15:51,948 --> 00:15:53,210
[Door opens]

232
00:15:53,250 --> 00:15:54,683
<i>CAROLINE: Luc.</i>

233
00:15:54,718 --> 00:15:57,278
<i>You've got a tiny error</i>
<i>in problem six... Oh!</i>

234
00:15:57,321 --> 00:15:59,789
<i>Luc! Oh.</i>

235
00:15:59,823 --> 00:16:01,757
It's nothing.

236
00:16:04,494 --> 00:16:06,257
It already stopped.

237
00:16:06,296 --> 00:16:09,459
Mother, the new teacher...

238
00:16:09,499 --> 00:16:11,899
wants us to correct
our own mistakes.

239
00:16:11,935 --> 00:16:14,460
I didn't tell you
how to correct the mistake...

240
00:16:14,504 --> 00:16:16,631
I just told you
that you made one.

241
00:17:01,451 --> 00:17:03,476
[Knock on door]

242
00:17:11,395 --> 00:17:13,386
[Moaning]

243
00:17:25,340 --> 00:17:27,331
[Footsteps]

244
00:17:36,552 --> 00:17:38,281
<i>WOMAN:</i>
<i>Not hungry, Monsieur le Comte?</i>

245
00:17:38,320 --> 00:17:40,220
The Lenten fast, Madame Rivet.

246
00:17:40,255 --> 00:17:42,951
Are you not supposed
to eat something?

247
00:17:45,594 --> 00:17:47,289
It's all right. Leave it.

248
00:18:25,634 --> 00:18:27,625
[Whispering]

249
00:18:44,686 --> 00:18:46,153
<i>VIANNE: Hello.</i>

250
00:18:47,756 --> 00:18:48,745
May I help you?

251
00:18:51,059 --> 00:18:53,823
It's expensive.
I don't waste money.

252
00:18:53,862 --> 00:18:56,854
I have a knack for
guessing people's favorites.

253
00:18:58,333 --> 00:19:03,293
These are your favorites.
Am I right?

254
00:19:03,338 --> 00:19:04,430
<i>VIANNE: On the house.</i>

255
00:19:04,473 --> 00:19:07,135
I think I'd better...
[Mumbling]

256
00:19:19,021 --> 00:19:20,750
WOMAN: Well...

257
00:19:20,789 --> 00:19:22,620
SECOND WOMAN:
This certainly is different.

258
00:19:22,658 --> 00:19:24,853
THIRD WOMAN:
Yes. Very different.

259
00:19:24,893 --> 00:19:26,485
<i>WOMAN: Look at that.</i>

260
00:19:26,528 --> 00:19:27,995
[Dog barks]

261
00:19:28,030 --> 00:19:29,691
WOMAN: Oh!

262
00:19:29,731 --> 00:19:31,995
Oh. I'm so sorry.

263
00:19:32,034 --> 00:19:34,059
Bonjour, Monsieur Blerot.

264
00:19:34,102 --> 00:19:37,071
Bonjour, Madame Audel.

265
00:19:47,282 --> 00:19:49,273
[Dog barking]

266
00:19:51,119 --> 00:19:52,143
<i>GUILLAUME:</i>
<i>No. Not that way, Charly.</i>

267
00:19:52,187 --> 00:19:53,518
<i>Come on.</i>

268
00:19:53,555 --> 00:19:55,648
Come in! Please.

269
00:19:55,691 --> 00:19:58,353
Come on, boy.

270
00:19:58,393 --> 00:19:59,655
I've got something for you.

271
00:20:06,368 --> 00:20:07,426
VIANNE: What's your name?

272
00:20:07,469 --> 00:20:10,029
GUILLAUME: Charly.
He's fourteen years old.

273
00:20:10,072 --> 00:20:12,666
That's ninety-eight
in human years.

274
00:20:12,708 --> 00:20:14,642
No, I meant your name.

275
00:20:14,676 --> 00:20:17,611
Oh! Guillaume Blerot.

276
00:20:17,646 --> 00:20:19,705
You're very kind.

277
00:20:19,748 --> 00:20:22,012
He has so few pleasures left.

278
00:20:22,050 --> 00:20:25,178
Would you care...

279
00:20:25,220 --> 00:20:27,347
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>Would you care to buy...</i>

280
00:20:27,389 --> 00:20:30,381
something special
for your lady friend?

281
00:20:30,425 --> 00:20:32,222
Lady friend?

282
00:20:32,260 --> 00:20:35,354
<i>VIANNE: The lovely woman</i>
<i>your dog was so fond of.</i>

283
00:20:35,397 --> 00:20:37,490
Oh.

284
00:20:37,532 --> 00:20:39,432
<i>VIANNE: Her favorite</i>
<i>is chocolate seashells.</i>

285
00:20:39,468 --> 00:20:40,765
That's my guess.

286
00:20:40,802 --> 00:20:43,396
Oh, no. I mustn't.

287
00:20:43,438 --> 00:20:46,373
Madame Audel is in mourning
for her husband.

288
00:20:46,408 --> 00:20:48,808
Oh, I'm sorry.

289
00:20:48,844 --> 00:20:50,539
When did he pass away?

290
00:20:50,579 --> 00:20:53,878
The war. German grenade.

291
00:20:53,915 --> 00:20:55,906
Hmm.

292
00:20:55,951 --> 00:20:58,784
Well, it's been fifteen years
since the war, so...

293
00:20:58,820 --> 00:21:00,378
Not that war.

294
00:21:00,422 --> 00:21:03,721
Monsieur Audel was killed
on January 12, 1917.

295
00:21:05,193 --> 00:21:07,923
It was quite a blow
to Madame Audel.

296
00:21:07,963 --> 00:21:09,988
Apparently so.

297
00:21:10,031 --> 00:21:12,556
- Hmm.
- Hmm.

298
00:21:14,002 --> 00:21:15,731
Bonjour, Mesdames!

299
00:21:15,771 --> 00:21:18,968
ALL: Bonjour, Monsieur le Comte.

300
00:21:23,111 --> 00:21:24,601
I wish all my tenants...

301
00:21:24,646 --> 00:21:26,944
were as reliable as you,
Madame Drou.

302
00:21:28,917 --> 00:21:31,249
How is the comtesse
enjoying Italy?

303
00:21:32,487 --> 00:21:36,446
Uh... She may be
extending her trip.

304
00:21:36,491 --> 00:21:39,255
<i>MADAME DROU: Ah, very nice.</i>

305
00:21:41,696 --> 00:21:44,824
Have either of you seen
the new shop across the square?

306
00:21:44,866 --> 00:21:47,300
The chocolaterie? Yes.

307
00:21:47,335 --> 00:21:49,769
Shameless, isn't it?

308
00:21:49,805 --> 00:21:51,602
[Clicks off]

309
00:21:51,640 --> 00:21:53,267
<i>REYNAUD:</i>
<i>The sheer nerve of the woman...</i>

310
00:21:53,308 --> 00:21:58,177
opening a chocolaterie
just in time for Lent.

311
00:22:00,248 --> 00:22:03,046
REYNAUD: The woman is brazen.

312
00:22:03,084 --> 00:22:05,848
My heart
goes out to that poor...

313
00:22:05,887 --> 00:22:08,117
illegitimate child of hers.

314
00:22:09,157 --> 00:22:10,146
Mmm.

315
00:22:13,762 --> 00:22:15,195
Bonjour.

316
00:22:18,066 --> 00:22:21,866
<i>[Singing] You ain't nothin'</i>
<i>but a hound dog</i>

317
00:22:21,903 --> 00:22:24,633
<i>Cryin' all the time</i>

318
00:22:24,673 --> 00:22:27,335
<i>PERE SINGING: You ain't nothin'</i>
<i>but a hound dog</i>

319
00:22:27,375 --> 00:22:29,434
<i>Cryin' all the time</i>

320
00:22:29,477 --> 00:22:31,809
<i>Well, you ain't never</i>
<i>caught no rabbit</i>

321
00:22:31,847 --> 00:22:34,008
<i>You ain't no friend of mine</i>

322
00:22:34,049 --> 00:22:35,277
Ooh, yeah!

323
00:22:35,317 --> 00:22:37,615
<i>REYNAUD:</i>
<i>A new addition to the liturgy?</i>

324
00:22:39,087 --> 00:22:41,487
I have a weakness
for American music...

325
00:22:41,523 --> 00:22:43,388
Monsieur le Comte.

326
00:22:43,425 --> 00:22:45,757
How long have you been with us,
Pere Henri?

327
00:22:45,794 --> 00:22:48,763
It will be five weeks.

328
00:22:48,797 --> 00:22:54,326
Your predecessor, Pere Michel,
he was with us for five decades.

329
00:22:54,369 --> 00:22:56,234
Yes, well...

330
00:22:56,271 --> 00:22:59,672
I only pray I can live up
to Pere Michel's example.

331
00:22:59,708 --> 00:23:03,109
Yes, that's my prayer also.

332
00:23:03,144 --> 00:23:05,408
I looked at your sermon,
as you requested.

333
00:23:05,447 --> 00:23:07,244
I've made one or two notes.

334
00:23:11,686 --> 00:23:13,051
You're very kind.

335
00:23:13,088 --> 00:23:15,784
Not at all.

336
00:23:15,824 --> 00:23:19,157
Oh, one more thing.

337
00:23:19,194 --> 00:23:21,526
If you haven't seen
the new chocolaterie...

338
00:23:21,563 --> 00:23:23,997
perhaps you might
like to take a look.

339
00:23:24,032 --> 00:23:26,125
It's important
to know one's enemy.

340
00:23:26,167 --> 00:23:29,068
Don't you think?

341
00:23:31,640 --> 00:23:34,074
<i>VIANNE: Hey, where's my kiss?</i>

342
00:23:36,211 --> 00:23:38,008
Aah! Ugh!

343
00:23:39,781 --> 00:23:40,975
Watch where you're going!

344
00:23:41,016 --> 00:23:41,983
<i>ANOUK: Excuse me!</i>

345
00:23:42,017 --> 00:23:44,247
Hello. Morning.

346
00:23:45,253 --> 00:23:49,212
What's the decor,
Early Mexican Brothel?

347
00:23:59,734 --> 00:24:02,828
No! If I need help,
I'll ask for it.

348
00:24:10,278 --> 00:24:11,973
What do you see in it?

349
00:24:12,013 --> 00:24:13,844
Not a damn thing.

350
00:24:13,881 --> 00:24:15,405
Come on. It's a game.

351
00:24:15,450 --> 00:24:17,941
<i>VIANNE: What do you see?</i>

352
00:24:17,986 --> 00:24:21,615
I see a cranky old woman
too tired to play games.

353
00:24:21,656 --> 00:24:24,989
<i>VIANNE: Hmm. I've got</i>
<i>just the thing for you.</i>

354
00:24:27,562 --> 00:24:30,463
<i>ARMANDE: That little girl</i>
<i>of yours, does she mind it?</i>

355
00:24:30,498 --> 00:24:31,692
Mind what?

356
00:24:31,733 --> 00:24:34,167
The way you move her
from place to place.

357
00:24:34,202 --> 00:24:38,605
Oh. She's doing fine.
I think it's good for her.

358
00:24:38,640 --> 00:24:42,041
<i>VIANNE: Seeing new places,</i>
<i>meeting new people.</i>

359
00:24:46,047 --> 00:24:48,379
Your cinnamon looks rancid.

360
00:24:48,416 --> 00:24:50,111
Well, it's not cinnamon.

361
00:24:50,151 --> 00:24:51,948
It's a special kind
of chili pepper.

362
00:24:51,986 --> 00:24:54,216
Chili pepper in hot chocolate?

363
00:24:54,255 --> 00:24:56,348
<i>VIANNE: Mm-hmm.</i>
<i>It'll give you a lift.</i>

364
00:24:57,358 --> 00:24:58,620
There.

365
00:25:06,934 --> 00:25:08,026
[Sniffing]

366
00:25:16,878 --> 00:25:19,938
It tastes like...

367
00:25:21,883 --> 00:25:23,510
I don't know.

368
00:25:25,186 --> 00:25:27,177
[Chuckles]

369
00:25:29,891 --> 00:25:31,085
<i>BOY: Hop, hop, hop, hop!</i>

370
00:25:31,125 --> 00:25:32,990
<i>SECOND BOY:</i>
<i>Where's your kangaroo?</i>

371
00:25:33,027 --> 00:25:34,221
<i>ANOUK: Uhh!</i>

372
00:25:34,262 --> 00:25:37,060
BO Y: Hop, hop, hop!
I'm your kangaroo now!

373
00:25:37,098 --> 00:25:39,066
[All yelling]

374
00:25:39,100 --> 00:25:40,328
Stop it!

375
00:25:40,368 --> 00:25:43,565
Stop it! Unh!

376
00:25:43,604 --> 00:25:46,505
Anouk! In this school,
we are civilized.

377
00:25:46,541 --> 00:25:48,441
We do not strike one another!

378
00:25:48,476 --> 00:25:50,307
ANOUK:
But they insulted Pantoufle!

379
00:25:50,344 --> 00:25:52,710
TEACHER: I don't care.
Didi, Dedou, come along!

380
00:25:54,982 --> 00:25:56,040
[Slams door]

381
00:25:56,084 --> 00:25:57,642
<i>TEACHER: And be quiet.</i>

382
00:25:59,320 --> 00:26:01,618
Where's Pantoufle?

383
00:26:01,656 --> 00:26:03,146
Shh!

384
00:26:04,492 --> 00:26:07,461
My mother says
you don't have a father.

385
00:26:07,495 --> 00:26:09,690
Sure I do.

386
00:26:09,731 --> 00:26:11,460
We just don't know who he is.

387
00:26:13,901 --> 00:26:15,459
I was out all night with him.

388
00:26:16,571 --> 00:26:19,005
We swam naked in the Tannes.

389
00:26:20,541 --> 00:26:23,237
At dawn, when I returned
to my house in my bed...

390
00:26:23,277 --> 00:26:25,609
my mother poked her head
in and said...

391
00:26:25,646 --> 00:26:27,705
"Wake up sleepyhead."

392
00:26:27,749 --> 00:26:29,512
[Laughing]

393
00:26:29,550 --> 00:26:31,381
She had no idea I'd been gone.

394
00:26:31,419 --> 00:26:33,080
[Laughing]

395
00:26:48,903 --> 00:26:51,235
Sure you didn't
put booze in there?

396
00:26:51,272 --> 00:26:54,002
Nah. Something better.

397
00:26:54,041 --> 00:26:56,635
Perhaps you should
give it to my daughter.

398
00:26:56,677 --> 00:27:00,374
<i>ARMANDE: Melt that chilly</i>
<i>disposition of hers.</i>

399
00:27:00,414 --> 00:27:02,405
You and Caroline have a problem?

400
00:27:02,450 --> 00:27:05,476
Do we have a problem?

401
00:27:06,888 --> 00:27:10,085
She won't let me
see my grandson.

402
00:27:10,124 --> 00:27:12,490
I'm cut off from him.

403
00:27:12,527 --> 00:27:14,791
<i>VIANNE: Why is that?</i>

404
00:27:14,829 --> 00:27:17,389
<i>Armande, why is that?</i>

405
00:27:18,699 --> 00:27:21,167
Oh, I'm a bad influence.

406
00:27:21,202 --> 00:27:24,933
'Cause I don't like her treating
him like a trained poodle.

407
00:27:24,972 --> 00:27:29,068
I swear, that boy doesn't piss
without her permission.

408
00:27:31,913 --> 00:27:33,505
<i>ARMANDE:</i>
<i>Ever since her husband died...</i>

409
00:27:33,548 --> 00:27:35,448
she's been so...

410
00:27:40,822 --> 00:27:43,985
The way she frets
and fusses over that boy.

411
00:27:44,025 --> 00:27:46,323
If only she'd let him run,
let him breathe...

412
00:27:46,360 --> 00:27:48,726
let him live.

413
00:27:48,763 --> 00:27:52,756
But she worries
that he will overexert himself.

414
00:27:54,001 --> 00:27:55,400
Not much danger of that.

415
00:27:55,436 --> 00:27:57,870
She won't even let
the poor kid ride a bicycle.

416
00:28:00,541 --> 00:28:03,374
Do you think
he'd like to see you?

417
00:28:05,680 --> 00:28:08,547
Do you have more of
those bean thingies, please?

418
00:28:08,583 --> 00:28:10,312
Oh, sure.

419
00:28:11,519 --> 00:28:13,612
<i>VIANNE: How many do you want?</i>

420
00:28:13,654 --> 00:28:14,985
How many have you got?

421
00:28:20,261 --> 00:28:22,422
Jack of hearts is a better
hunter than you, eh?

422
00:28:22,463 --> 00:28:25,955
Shoots the trump
from right out under your nose.

423
00:28:37,678 --> 00:28:39,145
Are you Serge Muscat?

424
00:28:39,180 --> 00:28:41,614
The one and only.
What's your pleasure?

425
00:28:41,649 --> 00:28:44,675
- Is your wife here?
- Josephine?

426
00:28:44,719 --> 00:28:48,780
Well, it depends what
you want with Josephine.

427
00:28:48,823 --> 00:28:52,224
Oh, she left this at my shop.

428
00:28:52,260 --> 00:28:55,627
Well, let me have it.
I'll give it to her.

429
00:28:55,663 --> 00:28:59,099
Oh, no. I'll give it
to her myself, thanks.

430
00:28:59,133 --> 00:29:02,796
<i>MAN: Got to go.</i>
<i>I'm late for supper.</i>

431
00:29:02,837 --> 00:29:05,533
<i>SECOND MAN:</i>
<i>But the game's not over yet.</i>

432
00:29:06,941 --> 00:29:08,135
Do you want to play?

433
00:29:09,510 --> 00:29:11,102
You know Belote?

434
00:29:11,145 --> 00:29:13,375
Of course I do.

435
00:29:13,414 --> 00:29:15,245
Sit down.

436
00:29:15,283 --> 00:29:17,046
[Footsteps]

437
00:29:17,084 --> 00:29:18,449
<i>VIANNE: Josephine.</i>

438
00:29:18,486 --> 00:29:20,078
[Clatter]

439
00:29:20,121 --> 00:29:21,884
What do you want?

440
00:29:21,923 --> 00:29:24,153
You forgot this.

441
00:29:24,191 --> 00:29:26,557
What do you want?

442
00:29:28,362 --> 00:29:29,920
To be your friend.

443
00:29:29,964 --> 00:29:33,730
I don't have friends.
Does Serge know you're here?

444
00:29:33,768 --> 00:29:35,998
Does it matter?

445
00:29:37,071 --> 00:29:40,006
Do me a favor.
Try one of these rose creams.

446
00:29:40,041 --> 00:29:44,239
Tell me if you think it's
a little heavy on the Cointreau.

447
00:29:58,926 --> 00:30:01,190
<i>SERGE: Josephine!</i>

448
00:30:08,602 --> 00:30:10,126
I'm coming!

449
00:30:10,171 --> 00:30:12,605
<i>JOSEPHINE: He talks about you.</i>

450
00:30:13,708 --> 00:30:14,868
He says you're indecent.

451
00:30:14,909 --> 00:30:16,774
He says you're an influence.

452
00:30:16,811 --> 00:30:19,302
You're a bad influence
for someone like me...

453
00:30:19,347 --> 00:30:22,373
I don't have to listen to a word
your husband has to say.

454
00:30:22,416 --> 00:30:24,782
JOSEPHINE: No, not Serge.

455
00:30:24,819 --> 00:30:26,309
Not him.

456
00:30:26,354 --> 00:30:28,652
Reynaud, the mayor.

457
00:30:30,091 --> 00:30:32,889
He... he talks about you.

458
00:30:38,866 --> 00:30:40,128
Time to go.

459
00:30:41,702 --> 00:30:43,932
Look what I won.

460
00:30:43,971 --> 00:30:46,599
That's good. Come on.

461
00:30:50,578 --> 00:30:52,273
[Man laughs]

462
00:30:56,450 --> 00:30:58,611
<i>MAN: Bonsoir.</i>

463
00:30:58,652 --> 00:31:00,847
<i>SECOND MAN: You see?</i>
<i>I said they'd be here.</i>

464
00:31:09,029 --> 00:31:11,020
[Birds chirping]

465
00:31:16,070 --> 00:31:19,164
Luc, mind if I take a peek?

466
00:31:19,206 --> 00:31:22,437
Oh, um...
It's not really...

467
00:31:22,476 --> 00:31:23,841
Show me.

468
00:31:23,877 --> 00:31:24,969
Oh.

469
00:31:26,346 --> 00:31:29,213
Well, I exaggerated
the angle of the head.

470
00:31:29,249 --> 00:31:31,444
You draw beautifully.

471
00:31:31,485 --> 00:31:33,180
What's your going rate?

472
00:31:33,220 --> 00:31:34,278
What?

473
00:31:34,321 --> 00:31:36,221
To do a portrait.

474
00:31:36,256 --> 00:31:38,121
How much would you charge?

475
00:31:38,158 --> 00:31:39,125
Oh, I...

476
00:31:39,159 --> 00:31:40,126
[Insect buzzing]

477
00:31:40,160 --> 00:31:43,618
I couldn't.
I'm not really a...

478
00:31:43,664 --> 00:31:47,259
Fifty francs?
Sound reasonable?

479
00:31:47,301 --> 00:31:48,825
It'd be great.

480
00:31:48,869 --> 00:31:49,836
[Vianne chuckles]

481
00:31:49,870 --> 00:31:52,202
When could you come by my shop?

482
00:31:53,340 --> 00:31:54,432
Oh.

483
00:31:54,475 --> 00:31:57,444
I'm... I'm really sorry, but...

484
00:31:57,478 --> 00:31:59,275
the comte forbids it.

485
00:32:03,317 --> 00:32:05,911
He spoke to Mama this morning...

486
00:32:05,953 --> 00:32:07,648
and a lot of others.

487
00:32:10,858 --> 00:32:12,120
Whatever you say.

488
00:32:12,159 --> 00:32:16,152
I wish I could. I really do.

489
00:32:17,865 --> 00:32:20,163
Thanks for showing me
your drawing.

490
00:32:25,672 --> 00:32:26,900
Wait.

491
00:32:39,620 --> 00:32:40,746
[Door slams]

492
00:32:45,826 --> 00:32:48,795
Am I breaking any laws?

493
00:32:48,829 --> 00:32:52,526
Tell me?
Am I hurting anyone?

494
00:32:52,566 --> 00:32:54,966
You're asking me my opinion?

495
00:32:55,002 --> 00:32:58,563
What exactly have you been
telling people about me?

496
00:32:58,605 --> 00:33:00,698
Only the truth, mademoiselle.

497
00:33:00,741 --> 00:33:03,266
Well...

498
00:33:03,310 --> 00:33:05,369
if you're expecting me...

499
00:33:05,412 --> 00:33:09,109
to just shrivel up
and blow away...

500
00:33:09,149 --> 00:33:11,310
you're going to be
highly disappointed.

501
00:33:17,925 --> 00:33:20,758
Let me try and put this
into perspective for you.

502
00:33:20,794 --> 00:33:23,194
<i>REYNAUD:</i>
<i>The first Comte de Reynaud...</i>

503
00:33:23,230 --> 00:33:27,564
expelled all the radical
Huguenots from this village.

504
00:33:27,601 --> 00:33:32,664
You and your truffles
present a far lesser challenge.

505
00:33:33,974 --> 00:33:36,841
<i>REYNAUD: You'll be</i>
<i>out of business by Easter.</i>

506
00:33:36,877 --> 00:33:38,845
I promise you that.

507
00:33:53,760 --> 00:33:54,886
Aah!

508
00:33:56,263 --> 00:33:57,594
Uhh!

509
00:33:57,631 --> 00:33:59,792
Aah! Aah!

510
00:34:01,001 --> 00:34:02,866
Uhh!

511
00:34:02,903 --> 00:34:04,894
[Baby crying]

512
00:34:07,808 --> 00:34:10,402
VIANNE: How long have you
been standing here?

513
00:34:12,479 --> 00:34:14,709
I forgot to pay you
for something the other day.

514
00:34:14,748 --> 00:34:16,045
I'm sorry.

515
00:34:16,083 --> 00:34:17,710
No, it was a gift.

516
00:34:17,751 --> 00:34:20,276
No. People talk.

517
00:34:20,320 --> 00:34:23,619
No, people would lie about me.

518
00:34:25,225 --> 00:34:27,250
I don't steal.

519
00:34:27,294 --> 00:34:30,388
Not on purpose. I...

520
00:34:30,430 --> 00:34:31,897
VIANNE: Yes, I know.

521
00:34:33,233 --> 00:34:35,463
It's nice to see you.

522
00:34:35,502 --> 00:34:38,471
Would you like to come in
for some chocolate?

523
00:34:50,951 --> 00:34:53,146
This is for you.

524
00:34:53,186 --> 00:34:54,483
How sweet of you.

525
00:34:54,521 --> 00:34:56,682
<i>VIANNE: Thank you.</i>

526
00:35:00,527 --> 00:35:02,119
Hmm, it's lovely.

527
00:35:06,867 --> 00:35:09,301
I heard you don't go to church.

528
00:35:10,771 --> 00:35:12,636
That's right.

529
00:35:13,807 --> 00:35:16,275
You won't last long here.

530
00:35:17,744 --> 00:35:19,974
<i>JOSEPHINE: People talk.</i>

531
00:35:22,182 --> 00:35:23,843
Oh, sorry.

532
00:35:23,884 --> 00:35:26,250
I'm behaving badly, aren't I?

533
00:35:26,286 --> 00:35:27,719
<i>VIANNE: No, it's OK.</i>

534
00:35:27,754 --> 00:35:29,278
<i>JOSEPHINE:</i>
<i>You don't misbehave here.</i>

535
00:35:29,323 --> 00:35:32,053
It's just not done,
did you know that?

536
00:35:33,560 --> 00:35:35,926
If you don't go to Confession...

537
00:35:35,962 --> 00:35:38,692
or if you don't
dig your flower beds...

538
00:35:38,732 --> 00:35:43,192
or if you don't pretend...

539
00:35:43,236 --> 00:35:46,728
that you want nothing
more in your life...

540
00:35:46,773 --> 00:35:49,139
than to serve your husband
three meals a day...

541
00:35:49,176 --> 00:35:52,009
and give him children
and vacuum under his ass...

542
00:35:52,045 --> 00:35:55,981
then... then you're crazy.

543
00:36:02,356 --> 00:36:06,816
You must think I'm stupid
to stay with him.

544
00:36:09,229 --> 00:36:12,392
No, I don't think you're stupid.

545
00:36:12,432 --> 00:36:16,630
Well, I am. I'm weak.

546
00:36:16,670 --> 00:36:19,002
I don't love my husband,
and I lie.

547
00:36:21,108 --> 00:36:25,135
Things could be different
for you, Josephine.

548
00:36:25,178 --> 00:36:28,079
Serge doesn't run the world.

549
00:36:28,115 --> 00:36:30,777
He might as well.

550
00:36:30,817 --> 00:36:32,910
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>Is that what you believe?</i>

551
00:36:32,953 --> 00:36:35,046
I know it.

552
00:36:35,088 --> 00:36:37,579
Oh.

553
00:36:37,624 --> 00:36:40,752
Then it must be true.

554
00:36:40,794 --> 00:36:42,284
My mistake.

555
00:36:47,834 --> 00:36:50,530
You make the most
wonderful chocolate.

556
00:36:51,972 --> 00:36:53,371
[Sips]

557
00:36:57,277 --> 00:36:59,211
Pantoufle wants
to hear the story...

558
00:36:59,246 --> 00:37:00,577
of grandmere and grandpere.

559
00:37:00,614 --> 00:37:02,047
Ohh!

560
00:37:02,082 --> 00:37:06,348
Don't say, "Not tonight."
You always say, "Not tonight."

561
00:37:06,386 --> 00:37:09,150
All right, all right.

562
00:37:09,189 --> 00:37:10,281
Oh.

563
00:37:12,826 --> 00:37:15,124
Your grandfather...

564
00:37:15,162 --> 00:37:18,131
George Rocher...

565
00:37:18,165 --> 00:37:22,795
was the young apothecary
of the town of Aulus-les-Bains.

566
00:37:22,836 --> 00:37:23,885
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>It was Anouk's favorite story.</i>

567
00:37:23,920 --> 00:37:24,934
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>It was Anouk's favorite story.</i>

568
00:37:24,970 --> 00:37:28,167
<i>Always told in the same words.</i>

569
00:37:28,207 --> 00:37:31,574
<i>George was honest,</i>
<i>prosperous...</i>

570
00:37:31,610 --> 00:37:34,738
<i>and trusted by his customers.</i>

571
00:37:34,780 --> 00:37:37,510
<i>But George was not content.</i>

572
00:37:37,550 --> 00:37:39,518
<i>He felt there</i>
<i>should be more to life...</i>

573
00:37:39,552 --> 00:37:41,816
<i>than dispensing liver oil.</i>

574
00:37:43,722 --> 00:37:46,589
<i>In the spring of 1927...</i>

575
00:37:46,625 --> 00:37:48,490
<i>the Societe Pharmeceutique...</i>

576
00:37:48,527 --> 00:37:51,291
<i>formed an expedition</i>
<i>to Central America...</i>

577
00:37:51,330 --> 00:37:53,491
<i>to study</i>
<i>the medicinal properties...</i>

578
00:37:53,532 --> 00:37:56,126
<i>of certain natural compounds.</i>

579
00:37:58,070 --> 00:38:01,904
<i>George was the expedition's</i>
<i>most eager volunteer.</i>

580
00:38:04,577 --> 00:38:08,104
<i>But his adventure</i>
<i>took a turn he did not expect.</i>

581
00:38:11,317 --> 00:38:15,344
<i>One night, he was invited</i>
<i>to drink unrefined cacao...</i>

582
00:38:15,387 --> 00:38:17,014
<i>with a pinch of chili.</i>

583
00:38:17,056 --> 00:38:21,254
<i>The very same drink</i>
<i>the ancient Maya...</i>

584
00:38:21,293 --> 00:38:23,761
<i>used in their sacred</i>
<i>ceremonies.</i>

585
00:38:25,865 --> 00:38:28,698
<i>The Maya believed</i>
<i>cacao held the power...</i>

586
00:38:28,734 --> 00:38:31,259
<i>to unlock hidden yearnings...</i>

587
00:38:33,506 --> 00:38:36,236
<i>and reveal destinies.</i>

588
00:38:39,011 --> 00:38:43,471
<i>And so it was</i>
<i>that George first saw Chitza.</i>

589
00:38:48,420 --> 00:38:51,389
<i>Now, George had been raised</i>
<i>a good Catholic...</i>

590
00:38:51,423 --> 00:38:55,086
<i>but in his romance</i>
<i>with Chitza...</i>

591
00:38:55,127 --> 00:38:57,357
<i>he was willing</i>
<i>to slightly bend the rules...</i>

592
00:38:57,396 --> 00:38:59,421
<i>of Christian courtship.</i>

593
00:39:01,167 --> 00:39:04,625
<i>The tribal elders</i>
<i>tried to warn George about her.</i>

594
00:39:04,670 --> 00:39:07,161
<i>She was one of the wanderers.</i>

595
00:39:07,206 --> 00:39:10,004
<i>Her people moved</i>
<i>with the North Wind...</i>

596
00:39:10,042 --> 00:39:11,600
<i>from village to village...</i>

597
00:39:11,644 --> 00:39:14,374
<i>dispensing ancient remedies...</i>

598
00:39:14,413 --> 00:39:16,813
<i>never settling down.</i>

599
00:39:16,849 --> 00:39:19,317
<i>Not a good choice for a bride.</i>

600
00:39:20,486 --> 00:39:23,421
<i>George did not</i>
<i>heed their warning...</i>

601
00:39:23,455 --> 00:39:25,889
<i>and for a while,</i>
<i>it seemed that he and Chitza...</i>

602
00:39:25,925 --> 00:39:28,450
<i>might lead a happy life</i>
<i>together in France.</i>

603
00:39:28,494 --> 00:39:31,224
[Wind blowing]

604
00:39:31,263 --> 00:39:35,791
<i>Alas, the clever North Wind</i>
<i>had other plans.</i>

605
00:39:37,836 --> 00:39:40,236
[Banging]

606
00:39:43,709 --> 00:39:47,304
<i>One morning,</i>
<i>George awoke to discover...</i>

607
00:39:47,346 --> 00:39:50,873
<i>that Chitza</i>
<i>and the little girl Vianne...</i>

608
00:39:50,916 --> 00:39:52,406
<i>had gone away.</i>

609
00:39:55,788 --> 00:39:57,346
<i>Mother and daughter...</i>

610
00:39:57,389 --> 00:40:00,517
<i>were fated to wander</i>
<i>from village to village...</i>

611
00:40:00,559 --> 00:40:04,586
<i>dispensing</i>
<i>ancient cacao remedies...</i>

612
00:40:04,630 --> 00:40:06,825
<i>traveling with the wind.</i>

613
00:40:08,167 --> 00:40:10,635
<i>Just as Chitza's people</i>
<i>had done...</i>

614
00:40:10,669 --> 00:40:11,795
<i>for generations.</i>

615
00:40:11,837 --> 00:40:14,101
VIANNE:
Just as Chitza's people...

616
00:40:14,139 --> 00:40:16,300
had done for generations.

617
00:40:18,644 --> 00:40:21,442
Will it just go on forever?

618
00:40:27,019 --> 00:40:28,509
Night, Mama.

619
00:40:46,472 --> 00:40:48,702
I appreciate your coming in,
Armande.

620
00:40:48,740 --> 00:40:53,109
What's so important
that I had to postpone my nap?

621
00:40:53,145 --> 00:40:55,511
I've got some chocolate cake.

622
00:41:06,592 --> 00:41:07,889
Grandmother.

623
00:41:07,926 --> 00:41:10,656
Grandmother... bonjour.

624
00:41:13,165 --> 00:41:14,860
May I...

625
00:41:17,236 --> 00:41:19,534
Would you like a cup of...?

626
00:41:19,571 --> 00:41:21,436
No, thank you.

627
00:41:21,473 --> 00:41:24,374
I'm just here to do a portrait.

628
00:41:24,409 --> 00:41:25,967
Mm-hmm.

629
00:41:26,011 --> 00:41:27,808
Whose?

630
00:41:27,846 --> 00:41:30,713
Yours, actually.

631
00:41:30,749 --> 00:41:33,217
<i>VIANNE: Is the light OK</i>
<i>where she's sitting?</i>

632
00:41:37,523 --> 00:41:41,550
I have something for you, boy.

633
00:41:41,593 --> 00:41:44,494
I've been carrying it around
since your last birthday.

634
00:41:48,267 --> 00:41:50,201
It's a book of poetry.

635
00:41:53,539 --> 00:41:55,700
Oh.

636
00:41:55,741 --> 00:41:56,969
Thank you.

637
00:41:57,009 --> 00:41:59,705
You don't like poetry?

638
00:41:59,745 --> 00:42:02,976
Oh, no. Of course I do.

639
00:42:03,015 --> 00:42:04,243
Yes.

640
00:42:04,283 --> 00:42:05,978
Neither do I.

641
00:42:07,352 --> 00:42:09,946
It's not that kind of poetry.

642
00:42:13,358 --> 00:42:16,657
And in a moment of weakness...

643
00:42:16,695 --> 00:42:18,686
I prayed to the Virgin Mother...

644
00:42:18,730 --> 00:42:21,665
to soothe Charly's soul
in his hour of suffering.

645
00:42:21,700 --> 00:42:26,660
You understand an animal
has no immortal soul.

646
00:42:26,705 --> 00:42:29,697
I understand, mon pere.

647
00:42:29,741 --> 00:42:32,266
Yet you flout God's law.

648
00:42:32,311 --> 00:42:35,246
<i>GUILLAUME:</i>
<i>I'm weak and a sinner.</i>

649
00:42:35,280 --> 00:42:37,009
PERE: What else?

650
00:42:39,284 --> 00:42:41,775
Impure thoughts.

651
00:42:41,820 --> 00:42:44,846
<i>GUILLAUME: The woman</i>
<i>who runs the chocolaterie.</i>

652
00:42:44,890 --> 00:42:46,187
Vianne Rocher?

653
00:42:46,225 --> 00:42:48,716
She suggested
I buy chocolate seashells...

654
00:42:48,760 --> 00:42:51,285
for the widow Audel.

655
00:42:51,330 --> 00:42:54,094
And, well...

656
00:42:54,132 --> 00:42:57,124
I guess that got me to thinking
about the widow Audel.

657
00:42:57,169 --> 00:43:01,071
At her age? At your age?

658
00:43:01,106 --> 00:43:04,906
Yes. And yes.

659
00:43:04,943 --> 00:43:09,471
And just what were you doing
in a chocolaterie during Lent?

660
00:43:09,514 --> 00:43:12,574
It was for Charly.

661
00:43:12,618 --> 00:43:15,746
Again you flout God's law.

662
00:43:18,023 --> 00:43:22,687
Well, but if Charly
has no soul...

663
00:43:22,728 --> 00:43:26,129
then there's no harm
in him breaking Lent.

664
00:43:26,164 --> 00:43:28,598
<i>GUILLAUME:</i>
<i>Isn't that so, mon pere?</i>

665
00:43:30,802 --> 00:43:33,293
Ten Hail Marys,
twenty Our Fathers.

666
00:43:34,840 --> 00:43:37,434
"Will she never have done,
then...

667
00:43:37,476 --> 00:43:42,106
"that ghoul queen of
a million dead bodies?

668
00:43:42,147 --> 00:43:44,775
"I see myself again...

669
00:43:44,816 --> 00:43:47,979
"skin rotten
with mud and pest...

670
00:43:48,020 --> 00:43:53,356
"worms in my armpits
and in my hair."

671
00:43:53,392 --> 00:43:55,758
It's perfectly wretched,
isn't it?

672
00:43:55,794 --> 00:43:57,455
Perfectly.

673
00:44:00,132 --> 00:44:03,431
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>Would you like some cake?</i>

674
00:44:03,468 --> 00:44:05,993
Ahem. I'm not supposed to.

675
00:44:06,038 --> 00:44:09,633
Don't worry so much
about not supposed to.

676
00:44:17,015 --> 00:44:18,505
ARMANDE: Hmm?

677
00:44:18,550 --> 00:44:20,211
Live a little.

678
00:44:23,088 --> 00:44:25,556
Oh, her hair appointment's
almost done.

679
00:44:27,426 --> 00:44:28,723
I have to go.

680
00:44:28,760 --> 00:44:31,991
- What about my picture?
- Next time.

681
00:44:34,032 --> 00:44:35,932
<i>LUC: Thank you for the cake.</i>

682
00:44:39,071 --> 00:44:41,801
Don't look so damn pleased
with yourself.

683
00:44:44,409 --> 00:44:46,707
[Knock on door]

684
00:44:50,716 --> 00:44:52,650
Stay here.

685
00:44:52,684 --> 00:44:56,552
[Pounding on door]

686
00:44:56,588 --> 00:44:58,613
[Pounding louder]

687
00:45:00,192 --> 00:45:03,593
JOSEPHINE: I did it.
[Laughs]

688
00:45:03,628 --> 00:45:06,563
I did it. He...

689
00:45:06,598 --> 00:45:08,566
He was so drunk.

690
00:45:08,600 --> 00:45:12,832
[Giggles]
He woke up.

691
00:45:12,871 --> 00:45:15,897
He woke up.
He saw me packing, but...

692
00:45:15,941 --> 00:45:17,374
So he tried to come after me...

693
00:45:17,409 --> 00:45:21,175
but I had already tied his feet
with his belt, and...

694
00:45:21,213 --> 00:45:22,874
Ha ha ha ha ha.

695
00:45:25,650 --> 00:45:28,346
Boom! Right on his face.

696
00:45:28,387 --> 00:45:29,820
[Laughing]

697
00:45:29,855 --> 00:45:34,258
Right there
on his big, red face.

698
00:45:34,292 --> 00:45:35,782
VIANNE: Mmm.

699
00:45:39,431 --> 00:45:41,558
VIANNE: Oh.

700
00:45:41,600 --> 00:45:43,761
Tsk. Ohh.

701
00:45:43,802 --> 00:45:47,795
It is so stupid, isn't it?

702
00:45:47,839 --> 00:45:50,933
I never blame him.

703
00:45:50,976 --> 00:45:55,743
Sometimes I even forget
what really happened.

704
00:45:59,017 --> 00:46:00,848
VIANNE: Now, now, now.

705
00:46:00,886 --> 00:46:02,820
[Crying]

706
00:46:04,756 --> 00:46:06,348
<i>VIANNE: Shh.</i>

707
00:46:08,260 --> 00:46:09,852
I saved her!

708
00:46:09,895 --> 00:46:12,989
You remember her father
collaborated with the Germans?

709
00:46:13,031 --> 00:46:16,967
Nobody wanted to touch her.
Except for me.

710
00:46:17,002 --> 00:46:18,902
And this is the way
she repays me?!

711
00:46:18,937 --> 00:46:20,302
Your anger is understandable.

712
00:46:20,338 --> 00:46:22,465
Anger?
Everybody's laughing at me!

713
00:46:22,507 --> 00:46:24,941
REYNAUD:
That is not your concern.

714
00:46:24,976 --> 00:46:27,308
Your concern is
the sacrament of marriage.

715
00:46:28,480 --> 00:46:31,574
SERGE: Yeah, of course.
The sacrament.

716
00:46:31,616 --> 00:46:34,278
<i>VIANNE: Dip the ganshbe</i>
<i>into the white chocolate.</i>

717
00:46:35,620 --> 00:46:37,247
Like this?

718
00:46:37,289 --> 00:46:40,383
Good.
Yes, shake it, a little.

719
00:46:40,425 --> 00:46:41,414
Good.

720
00:46:41,460 --> 00:46:43,792
Put it on the parchment sheet.

721
00:46:43,829 --> 00:46:46,059
You're doing great.

722
00:46:46,097 --> 00:46:47,428
[Door opens]

723
00:46:47,466 --> 00:46:50,560
Oh. I'll be right back.

724
00:46:57,943 --> 00:47:00,309
Oh. Good morning.

725
00:47:00,345 --> 00:47:04,042
Can I interest you
in some Nipples of Venus?

726
00:47:04,082 --> 00:47:06,846
Rumor has it that you are
harboring Madame Muscat.

727
00:47:06,885 --> 00:47:09,012
<i>REYNAUD: Is that true?</i>

728
00:47:09,054 --> 00:47:10,817
You make her sound
like a fugitive.

729
00:47:10,856 --> 00:47:13,324
She is a fugitive,
from her marriage vows...

730
00:47:13,358 --> 00:47:15,758
which have been
sanctified by God.

731
00:47:17,429 --> 00:47:18,987
Josephine?

732
00:47:19,030 --> 00:47:21,521
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>Come out here a minute.</i>

733
00:47:24,669 --> 00:47:27,467
Let His Radiance
have a look at you, hmm?

734
00:47:32,844 --> 00:47:35,574
<i>VIANNE: Is that sanctified</i>
<i>enough for you?</i>

735
00:47:35,614 --> 00:47:36,740
<i>It's not the first time.</i>

736
00:47:36,781 --> 00:47:38,646
I'm truly sorry.

737
00:47:40,652 --> 00:47:43,086
<i>REYNAUD:</i>
<i>You should have come to me.</i>

738
00:47:43,121 --> 00:47:46,682
Your husband will be made
to repent for this.

739
00:47:46,725 --> 00:47:51,029
Tell him to repent
on someone else's head.

740
00:47:51,162 --> 00:47:53,062
REYNAUD: Come on. In!

741
00:47:53,097 --> 00:47:54,086
SERGE: Monsieur le Comte!

742
00:47:54,132 --> 00:47:56,327
I'm going to make
an example of you.

743
00:47:56,367 --> 00:48:00,098
In there. He's ready.

744
00:48:00,138 --> 00:48:02,436
Well, but confession
must be made...

745
00:48:02,473 --> 00:48:04,532
in the spirit of contrition.

746
00:48:04,575 --> 00:48:07,066
Have you come
in the spirit of contrition?

747
00:48:07,111 --> 00:48:08,442
Contrition, yes.

748
00:48:08,479 --> 00:48:10,242
He's ready.

749
00:48:10,281 --> 00:48:11,771
[Sighs]

750
00:48:13,284 --> 00:48:17,186
<i>BAPTISTE: Licentiousness,</i>
<i>idolatry, sorcery...</i>

751
00:48:17,221 --> 00:48:19,212
gluttony, and drunkenness.

752
00:48:19,257 --> 00:48:21,748
Correct.

753
00:48:21,793 --> 00:48:25,456
And what are the three
conditions for mortal sin?

754
00:48:25,496 --> 00:48:27,794
Serge?

755
00:48:27,832 --> 00:48:29,527
Mortal sin...

756
00:48:31,536 --> 00:48:35,370
is sin whose object is...

757
00:48:36,641 --> 00:48:38,472
committed by...

758
00:48:38,509 --> 00:48:42,172
deliberate... consequence.

759
00:48:42,213 --> 00:48:44,374
Incorrect. Didi?

760
00:48:44,415 --> 00:48:48,408
Mortal sin is sin
whose object is grave matter...

761
00:48:48,453 --> 00:48:50,921
which is committed
with full knowledge...

762
00:48:50,955 --> 00:48:52,684
and deliberate consent.

763
00:48:52,723 --> 00:48:53,712
<i>PERE: Correct.</i>

764
00:48:53,758 --> 00:48:55,020
Gah!

765
00:49:04,235 --> 00:49:05,702
VIANNE:
So, how do you know...

766
00:49:05,736 --> 00:49:07,795
if the coverture
is properly tempered?

767
00:49:07,839 --> 00:49:13,436
JOSEPHINE: You check to see
if it's at body temperature.

768
00:49:13,478 --> 00:49:15,912
Then you dip
the palette knife...

769
00:49:15,947 --> 00:49:18,507
to see that the coverture
hardens on it evenly.

770
00:49:18,549 --> 00:49:19,573
Correct.

771
00:49:21,018 --> 00:49:22,212
Closer.

772
00:49:25,256 --> 00:49:26,814
Aah.

773
00:49:26,858 --> 00:49:29,622
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>In the village, time passed.</i>

774
00:49:34,832 --> 00:49:38,461
<i>And the chocolaterie</i>
<i>did not go out of business.</i>

775
00:49:45,877 --> 00:49:47,037
[Drops package]

776
00:49:53,451 --> 00:49:54,543
[Charly yelps]

777
00:49:57,288 --> 00:49:59,222
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>The Comte de Reynaud...</i>

778
00:49:59,257 --> 00:50:02,624
<i>felt himself being drawn</i>
<i>into a strange crusade.</i>

779
00:50:05,963 --> 00:50:09,831
<i>His struggle to transform Serge</i>
<i>into a gentleman...</i>

780
00:50:09,867 --> 00:50:13,735
<i>became more</i>
<i>than an act of good will.</i>

781
00:50:13,771 --> 00:50:16,365
<i>It became a test...</i>

782
00:50:16,407 --> 00:50:20,138
<i>a holy war between chateau...</i>

783
00:50:20,178 --> 00:50:22,476
<i>and chocolaterie.</i>

784
00:50:43,100 --> 00:50:45,261
[Charly howls]

785
00:50:45,303 --> 00:50:46,827
<i>LUC: Each time, I...</i>

786
00:50:46,871 --> 00:50:49,772
I tell myself
it's the last time.

787
00:50:49,807 --> 00:50:51,900
But then I...

788
00:50:51,943 --> 00:50:54,844
I get a whiff
of a hot chocolate.

789
00:50:54,879 --> 00:50:57,643
Or those moon things.

790
00:50:57,682 --> 00:50:58,979
<i>AUDEL: Chocolate seashells.</i>

791
00:50:59,016 --> 00:51:02,850
So small, so plain, so innocent.

792
00:51:02,887 --> 00:51:05,219
I thought,
just one little taste...

793
00:51:05,256 --> 00:51:07,247
it can't do any harm.

794
00:51:07,291 --> 00:51:08,986
But it turned out
that they were filled...

795
00:51:09,026 --> 00:51:11,460
with rich, sinful...

796
00:51:11,495 --> 00:51:12,587
YVETTE: Buttery filling...

797
00:51:12,630 --> 00:51:14,996
and it melts,
God forgive me...

798
00:51:15,032 --> 00:51:17,728
it melts ever-so-slowly
on your tongue...

799
00:51:17,768 --> 00:51:19,963
and tortures you with pleasure.

800
00:51:20,004 --> 00:51:22,495
<i>PERE: Against You alone,</i>
<i>have I sinned...</i>

801
00:51:22,540 --> 00:51:25,100
<i>and done what is evil</i>
<i>in Your sight.</i>

802
00:51:25,142 --> 00:51:27,440
[Plastic crinkling]

803
00:51:27,478 --> 00:51:29,002
[Crinkling stops]

804
00:51:29,046 --> 00:51:31,207
<i>Indeed I was born guilty...</i>

805
00:51:31,249 --> 00:51:34,844
<i>a sinner when my mother</i>
<i>conceived me.</i>

806
00:51:34,885 --> 00:51:36,750
<i>You desire truth</i>
<i>in the inward being...</i>

807
00:51:36,787 --> 00:51:40,314
<i>therefore teach me wisdom</i>
<i>in my secret heart.</i>

808
00:51:40,358 --> 00:51:41,484
[Swallows]

809
00:51:43,861 --> 00:51:45,795
<i>STORYTELLER:</i>
<i>Now, the comte was no fool.</i>

810
00:51:45,830 --> 00:51:48,765
<i>Though he hoped</i>
<i>to redeem Serge...</i>

811
00:51:48,799 --> 00:51:50,824
<i>he knew that</i>
<i>this redemption alone...</i>

812
00:51:50,868 --> 00:51:52,165
<i>would not be enough...</i>

813
00:51:52,203 --> 00:51:54,535
<i>to regain control</i>
<i>over the village.</i>

814
00:51:54,572 --> 00:51:57,564
<i>He understood</i>
<i>that some larger lesson...</i>

815
00:51:57,608 --> 00:51:59,235
<i>needed to be taught.</i>

816
00:52:03,981 --> 00:52:05,812
<i>Some greater problem...</i>

817
00:52:05,850 --> 00:52:10,082
<i>needed to be identified</i>
<i>and solved.</i>

818
00:52:12,523 --> 00:52:16,323
<i>Little did the comte suspect</i>
<i>that his greater problem...</i>

819
00:52:16,360 --> 00:52:18,726
<i>would arrive</i>
<i>one quiet afternoon...</i>

820
00:52:18,763 --> 00:52:21,630
<i>in the dull green waters</i>
<i>of the river Tannes.</i>

821
00:52:21,666 --> 00:52:23,930
[Children playing]

822
00:52:25,636 --> 00:52:27,069
You're it!

823
00:52:28,773 --> 00:52:29,933
You're it!

824
00:52:29,974 --> 00:52:31,464
Hey, look!

825
00:52:36,147 --> 00:52:37,774
<i>BOY: I'm over here!</i>

826
00:52:47,491 --> 00:52:50,119
<i>VIANNE: You've never really</i>
<i>told me what the problem is...</i>

827
00:52:50,161 --> 00:52:51,958
between you and Caroline.

828
00:52:51,996 --> 00:52:54,294
'Cause it's none of
your damn business.

829
00:52:55,533 --> 00:52:57,592
[Armande sighs]

830
00:52:57,635 --> 00:52:59,762
<i>ARMANDE:</i>
<i>I'm an embarrassment to her.</i>

831
00:53:01,872 --> 00:53:06,832
I swear, I read dirty books.

832
00:53:06,877 --> 00:53:09,607
I eat and drink what I like.

833
00:53:11,282 --> 00:53:12,977
And sin of sins...

834
00:53:13,017 --> 00:53:16,509
I refuse to go to Les Mimosas.

835
00:53:16,554 --> 00:53:21,116
<i>JOSEPHINE: When I was a kid,</i>
<i>we called it Le Mortoir.</i>

836
00:53:21,158 --> 00:53:25,060
<i>It's a nursing home for old...</i>

837
00:53:25,096 --> 00:53:26,893
It's in Toulouse.

838
00:53:26,931 --> 00:53:28,398
Mmm.

839
00:53:28,432 --> 00:53:30,764
<i>ARMANDE: Caroline loves</i>
<i>the thought of a nurse...</i>

840
00:53:30,801 --> 00:53:34,396
with a clipboard
recording my bowel movements.

841
00:53:34,438 --> 00:53:36,668
<i>ANOUK:</i>
<i>Mama, Mama, come quick!</i>

842
00:53:36,707 --> 00:53:38,868
They're here!
They've come to Lansquenet!

843
00:53:38,909 --> 00:53:42,208
- Slow down, Anouk. Who's here?
- Pirates!

844
00:53:42,246 --> 00:53:43,213
Come on!

845
00:53:43,247 --> 00:53:45,442
- Why can't we stay?
- Come on!

846
00:53:45,483 --> 00:53:47,917
<i>BOY: But why can't we stay?</i>

847
00:53:47,952 --> 00:53:48,919
OK, enough.

848
00:53:48,953 --> 00:53:52,184
BO Y: But, Mama,
just a little bit.

849
00:53:52,223 --> 00:53:54,316
<i>MAMA: Come on.</i>

850
00:53:54,358 --> 00:53:56,724
VIANNE: Hello. How are you?

851
00:53:58,396 --> 00:54:00,261
ANOUK:
Anybody got a sweet tooth?

852
00:54:00,297 --> 00:54:02,231
[Guitar playing]

853
00:54:12,610 --> 00:54:14,601
[Guitar continues playing]

854
00:54:19,984 --> 00:54:21,975
I bet he's the captain.

855
00:54:25,289 --> 00:54:27,382
<i>VIANNE: Anouk, don't do that.</i>

856
00:54:27,425 --> 00:54:30,121
<i>Anouk, don't do that, please.</i>

857
00:54:30,161 --> 00:54:32,527
- How do you do?
- Sorry.

858
00:54:32,563 --> 00:54:34,292
<i>ROUX: I'd like to apologize.</i>

859
00:54:34,331 --> 00:54:37,391
For all of us. Sincerely.

860
00:54:37,435 --> 00:54:38,766
What for?

861
00:54:38,803 --> 00:54:42,204
ROUX: For whatever it is
you're here to accuse us of.

862
00:54:42,239 --> 00:54:44,070
Why would I do that?

863
00:54:44,108 --> 00:54:48,807
Well, because we river rats
are the dregs of society.

864
00:54:48,846 --> 00:54:51,144
With horrible diseases
and criminal impulses.

865
00:54:51,182 --> 00:54:54,151
[Chuckles]
Sounds terrifying.

866
00:54:54,185 --> 00:54:55,812
Is it true?

867
00:54:55,853 --> 00:54:59,414
It's what you townspeople
always seem to think, isn't it?

868
00:54:59,457 --> 00:55:02,187
This is not my town.
Sorry.

869
00:55:02,226 --> 00:55:03,510
<i>ROUX: Well, then,</i>
<i>what do you want?</i>

870
00:55:03,545 --> 00:55:04,794
<i>ROUX: Well, then,</i>
<i>what do you want?</i>

871
00:55:04,828 --> 00:55:06,489
Are you here to save us?

872
00:55:06,529 --> 00:55:08,793
Are you
the Catholic Aid Society?

873
00:55:08,832 --> 00:55:11,198
French Family League?
Communist Workers?

874
00:55:11,234 --> 00:55:12,758
Which idea are you selling?

875
00:55:12,802 --> 00:55:14,269
Chocolate.

876
00:55:14,304 --> 00:55:16,033
I'm sorry, chocolate?

877
00:55:16,072 --> 00:55:17,937
<i>ANOUK: What's a river rat?</i>

878
00:55:17,974 --> 00:55:19,874
Is it like a pirate?

879
00:55:19,909 --> 00:55:20,967
[Vianne chuckles]

880
00:55:21,010 --> 00:55:22,409
Yeah, you could say that.

881
00:55:22,445 --> 00:55:24,413
You could.

882
00:55:24,447 --> 00:55:26,972
Have a look
at my treasure chest.

883
00:55:27,016 --> 00:55:29,246
VIANNE: Oh.

884
00:55:29,285 --> 00:55:31,344
Let me guess, they're for sale.

885
00:55:31,387 --> 00:55:32,854
ROUX: As a matter of fact,
they are.

886
00:55:32,889 --> 00:55:35,414
For a mere thirty francs apiece.

887
00:55:35,458 --> 00:55:37,722
You laugh? I can get fifty
for them in Paris.

888
00:55:37,760 --> 00:55:40,490
Then go to Paris.

889
00:55:48,705 --> 00:55:50,138
We'll take two, please.

890
00:55:50,173 --> 00:55:51,140
You'll take two?

891
00:55:51,174 --> 00:55:52,732
Yes, please, absolutely.

892
00:55:52,775 --> 00:55:55,335
<i>ROUX: OK.</i>

893
00:55:55,378 --> 00:55:58,074
<i>VIANNE: I don't know</i>
<i>if I have the right change.</i>

894
00:55:58,114 --> 00:55:59,081
<i>Just a minute.</i>

895
00:55:59,115 --> 00:56:00,912
They're beautiful.

896
00:56:00,950 --> 00:56:03,384
<i>ROUX: Ireland's finest.</i>

897
00:56:03,419 --> 00:56:04,545
Thanks.

898
00:56:04,587 --> 00:56:06,646
Thank you. Listen...

899
00:56:06,689 --> 00:56:08,850
I should probably warn you.

900
00:56:08,892 --> 00:56:12,658
You make friends with us,
you'll make enemies of others.

901
00:56:12,695 --> 00:56:14,629
That a promise?

902
00:56:17,734 --> 00:56:19,634
It's a guarantee.

903
00:56:28,478 --> 00:56:30,469
[Laughing]

904
00:56:32,248 --> 00:56:34,546
<i>ALPHONSE: What's he up to?</i>

905
00:56:34,584 --> 00:56:37,553
<i>JEAN-MARC:</i>
<i>Maybe he's joining the circus.</i>

906
00:56:40,490 --> 00:56:42,822
[Door rattles]

907
00:56:42,859 --> 00:56:44,724
Sorry, we're closed!

908
00:56:58,708 --> 00:57:01,700
Josephine, you look different.

909
00:57:01,744 --> 00:57:04,406
So do you.

910
00:57:06,950 --> 00:57:10,317
I just want to tell you
that I am so sorry.

911
00:57:10,353 --> 00:57:13,083
<i>SERGE: For everything.</i>

912
00:57:13,122 --> 00:57:15,056
<i>But I've changed.</i>

913
00:57:15,091 --> 00:57:18,458
You see,
God has made me a new man.

914
00:57:20,530 --> 00:57:23,897
I ask you, I beg you...

915
00:57:23,933 --> 00:57:26,458
please accept my apology.

916
00:57:38,114 --> 00:57:39,604
I accept.

917
00:57:42,685 --> 00:57:46,951
I promise, from now on,
everything will be different.

918
00:57:49,092 --> 00:57:51,583
Everything already
is different, Serge.

919
00:57:51,627 --> 00:57:53,094
[Chuckles]

920
00:57:53,129 --> 00:57:55,597
Well, I mean,
when you come home.

921
00:57:55,631 --> 00:57:57,292
Home?

922
00:57:59,969 --> 00:58:04,201
Thanks for the apology.
The flowers are lovely.

923
00:58:04,240 --> 00:58:06,333
No, please don't, Josephine.

924
00:58:06,376 --> 00:58:09,140
We are still married
in the eyes of God.

925
00:58:09,178 --> 00:58:11,738
Then he must be blind.

926
00:58:14,183 --> 00:58:15,946
[Locks door]

927
00:58:18,287 --> 00:58:21,188
<i>JEAN-MARC: The council</i>
<i>has no legal authority...</i>

928
00:58:21,224 --> 00:58:22,816
to force them to move.

929
00:58:22,859 --> 00:58:25,657
The riverbank is public land.

930
00:58:25,695 --> 00:58:27,822
[Grumbling]

931
00:58:29,432 --> 00:58:32,595
The mayor wishes
to say a few words.

932
00:58:32,635 --> 00:58:33,932
REYNAUD: If I may...

933
00:58:33,970 --> 00:58:35,938
ladies and gentlemen
of the council.

934
00:58:37,473 --> 00:58:41,910
These people are
rootless, godless drifters.

935
00:58:41,944 --> 00:58:43,775
<i>MAN: That's right!</i>

936
00:58:43,813 --> 00:58:45,781
<i>REYNAUD: Theirs is the way</i>
<i>of slovenly pleasure.</i>

937
00:58:45,815 --> 00:58:47,214
<i>MAN: Yes.</i>

938
00:58:47,250 --> 00:58:51,380
They would contaminate
the spirit of our quiet town.

939
00:58:51,421 --> 00:58:54,652
<i>REYNAUD:</i>
<i>The innocence of our children.</i>

940
00:58:54,690 --> 00:58:57,420
Now, the chairman of the council
is quite right.

941
00:58:57,460 --> 00:59:00,691
We cannot force them to leave.

942
00:59:00,730 --> 00:59:02,163
<i>MAN: Why not?</i>

943
00:59:02,198 --> 00:59:05,292
But we can help them
to understand...

944
00:59:05,334 --> 00:59:07,325
that they are not welcome.

945
00:59:07,370 --> 00:59:09,873
[Muttering]

946
00:59:11,574 --> 00:59:14,042
[Glass shatters]

947
00:59:15,144 --> 00:59:16,634
Josephine?

948
00:59:19,482 --> 00:59:23,509
Josephine, you think
you can just walk out on me?

949
00:59:23,553 --> 00:59:25,453
<i>SERGE: You stupid woman!</i>

950
00:59:25,488 --> 00:59:28,980
<i>Worthless cow!</i>
<i>You're nothing without me.</i>

951
00:59:29,025 --> 00:59:31,493
<i>You can't even use a skillet!</i>

952
00:59:32,896 --> 00:59:36,457
<i>Can't even put</i>
<i>a goddamn meal on the table.</i>

953
00:59:36,499 --> 00:59:38,126
He's inside.

954
00:59:38,167 --> 00:59:40,727
<i>JOSEPHINE:</i>
<i>He's here. Oh, God.</i>

955
00:59:40,770 --> 00:59:42,328
<i>SERGE:</i>
<i>I need to talk to you.</i>

956
00:59:43,773 --> 00:59:45,798
Please open the door.
I know...

957
00:59:45,842 --> 00:59:48,276
<i>- Mama!</i>
<i>- Come help me!</i>

958
00:59:48,311 --> 00:59:50,745
<i>SERGE: Open the door.</i>

959
00:59:50,780 --> 00:59:54,409
<i>Open the door.</i>
<i>I just want to talk to you.</i>

960
00:59:54,450 --> 00:59:56,315
VIANNE:
Go sleep it off, Serge!

961
00:59:56,352 --> 00:59:58,820
<i>SERGE: Ah, you shut up,</i>
<i>you bitch!</i>

962
00:59:58,855 --> 01:00:01,824
You've caused enough
trouble already!

963
01:00:01,858 --> 01:00:02,825
You...

964
01:00:02,859 --> 01:00:04,451
[Pounding on door]

965
01:00:04,494 --> 01:00:05,552
Unh!

966
01:00:05,595 --> 01:00:06,562
<i>SERGE: Open this door!</i>

967
01:00:06,596 --> 01:00:07,790
Mama!

968
01:00:07,830 --> 01:00:10,298
Aah! Aah!

969
01:00:10,333 --> 01:00:11,300
<i>JOSEPHINE: Oh, my God!</i>

970
01:00:11,334 --> 01:00:13,302
[Shouting]

971
01:00:13,336 --> 01:00:15,236
Stay away from me.

972
01:00:16,940 --> 01:00:18,498
Aah!

973
01:00:18,541 --> 01:00:21,567
- Come here now!
- Aah!

974
01:00:21,611 --> 01:00:23,203
SERGE: Aah!

975
01:00:23,246 --> 01:00:25,441
Why, you meddling bitch!

976
01:00:31,187 --> 01:00:32,518
You...

977
01:00:33,523 --> 01:00:35,514
[Choking]

978
01:00:37,827 --> 01:00:39,158
Ahh!

979
01:00:39,195 --> 01:00:41,993
VIANNE: Aah! Aah!

980
01:00:42,031 --> 01:00:43,862
Aah! Aah!

981
01:00:45,935 --> 01:00:48,495
Who says I can't use a skillet?

982
01:00:48,538 --> 01:00:49,800
[Drops skillet]

983
01:00:49,839 --> 01:00:51,830
[Laughs]

984
01:00:53,509 --> 01:00:55,670
[Bell tolling]

985
01:00:58,614 --> 01:00:59,774
Bonjour, monsieur.

986
01:00:59,816 --> 01:01:01,477
Bonjour, monsieur.

987
01:01:08,358 --> 01:01:10,223
Bonjour.

988
01:01:13,329 --> 01:01:15,297
Wonderful.

989
01:01:15,331 --> 01:01:16,457
Come on.

990
01:01:16,499 --> 01:01:19,696
Up. Come on. Up.

991
01:01:19,736 --> 01:01:20,828
[Groans]

992
01:01:20,870 --> 01:01:22,804
Come on.

993
01:01:22,839 --> 01:01:24,431
[Laughter]

994
01:01:24,474 --> 01:01:27,341
His skull can't be
as thick as we thought.

995
01:01:27,377 --> 01:01:29,208
[All laugh]

996
01:01:29,245 --> 01:01:32,737
<i>VIANNE:</i>
<i>It was like swatting a fly.</i>

997
01:01:36,853 --> 01:01:40,550
Ohh. The worst is over.

998
01:01:40,590 --> 01:01:42,649
He found out
what you're made of.

999
01:01:42,692 --> 01:01:44,683
[Laughs] So did I.

1000
01:01:47,897 --> 01:01:50,058
- Hi.
- Hey.

1001
01:01:50,099 --> 01:01:51,191
Mmm!

1002
01:01:52,668 --> 01:01:53,999
How long have we got?

1003
01:01:54,037 --> 01:01:55,902
She's at the hairdresser
for an hour.

1004
01:01:55,938 --> 01:01:57,166
[Gasps]

1005
01:01:57,206 --> 01:01:59,071
Fuffi?

1006
01:01:59,108 --> 01:02:00,507
<i>CAROLINE: Fuffi.</i>

1007
01:02:00,543 --> 01:02:02,010
I'm so sorry, but I have
to break the appointment.

1008
01:02:02,045 --> 01:02:03,535
FRANCOISE: Is something wrong?

1009
01:02:03,579 --> 01:02:05,069
CAROLINE: No. I volunteered
to distribute these.

1010
01:02:05,114 --> 01:02:08,174
I promised the comte I'd have
them out by the end of the day.

1011
01:02:08,217 --> 01:02:10,185
FRANCOISE: Count me in.

1012
01:02:10,219 --> 01:02:13,086
Not that I expect any of them
to stop by for a hairstyle.

1013
01:02:13,122 --> 01:02:14,282
<i>CAROLINE: It's not just that.</i>

1014
01:02:14,323 --> 01:02:15,654
<i>The comte feels</i>
<i>we must stand firm.</i>

1015
01:02:15,691 --> 01:02:17,886
<i>We cannot trust these people.</i>

1016
01:02:17,927 --> 01:02:20,225
<i>Before you know it,</i>
<i>they'll be doing jobs for food.</i>

1017
01:02:20,263 --> 01:02:21,287
<i>They'll be begging</i>
<i>at our doors.</i>

1018
01:02:21,330 --> 01:02:23,230
<i>FRANCOISE: Not at this door.</i>

1019
01:02:23,266 --> 01:02:25,791
<i>CAROLINE: Good, Fuffi, good.</i>

1020
01:02:25,835 --> 01:02:26,802
[Exhales]
